explanation:
To determine whether any operations in OS_FileOpenCheck constitute dead code (i.e., their removal would not affect program behaviour), the analyzer needs the following symbols and why:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro may alter control flow (e.g., return, assert, or print) on invalid Filename. Knowing its expansion is required to see whether the function can exit early, which affects whether subsequent code is ever executed.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Passed to OS_ObjectIdIterateActive to select which object table is iterated. The object type determines whether the iteration will examine file/stream objects relevant to this function.

- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive: Initializes the iterator for the chosen object type. Its behaviour (which set of objects becomes traversed) is necessary to know if the while-loop can ever run and thus whether loop body statements are potentially live.

- OS_object_iter_t: The iterator type definition (including the token field) is needed to understand what iter.token represents and how it is advanced/used. This affects whether the OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET lookup is valid and whether any iteration yields records that make the condition true.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: Controls loop progress and determines whether the loop body executes for any elements. Its return semantics (boolean, side effects) are essential to decide if loop body is reachable/observable.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: Might have side effects (cleanup, transactions) that affect program behaviour even if loop body is skipped; needed to see if removing parts would change behaviour.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/function that maps iter.token to a pointer to an OS_stream_internal_record_t. Its semantics (indexing, bounds checks, use of OS_ObjectIndexFromToken) determine whether the retrieved pointer is valid and whether the comparisons in the loop have effect.

- OS_stream_table: The actual table/mapping that OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET reads. The table contents/structure determine whether any entry can satisfy the condition (socket_domain == INVALID and matching name), which decides whether the assignment and break are live.

- OS_stream_internal_record_t: Definition of the stream record (fields socket_domain and stream_name types). Needed to know how comparisons behave (e.g., stream_name pointer vs. fixed array) and whether accessing these fields has side effects or can be optimized away.

- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID: The enumerator/constant used in the comparison. Required to know which domain values are possible and whether any stream records could match this value, affecting whether the conditional body can run.

- OS_SUCCESS and OS_ERROR: Return-value constants used by the function. To judge dead code, we must know whether changing or removing the assignment to return_code (and the eventual return) would modify observable behaviour.

- strcmp: Standard comparison used to test the filename equality. Its semantics (pure function, no side effects) are relevant to determine whether the comparison can have observable side effects and thus whether the call is dead or necessary.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Often used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or iterator internals to translate tokens to indices. Knowing its behaviour (e.g., whether tokens can map to stream entries) helps decide if the lookup can yield entries that make the condition true.

Collectively, these symbols define the control-flow, the iteration domain, and the data tested by the conditional inside the loop. Without them you cannot conclude whether the loop body (the strcmp and assignment to return_code followed by break) ever affects program behaviour and therefore whether that code is dead.
